  "text": "The translation of our activity-dependent stimulation paradigm to practical clinical applications would be promoted with less invasive procedures. Instead of recording neural activity with intracortical electrodes, it is possible to record activity-dependent cortical potentials less invasively through surface electrodes [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] or to use muscle activity as a surrogate of cortical activity [CITATION_3] . The intraspinal stimulation that we used is known to activate many afferent fibers of passage [CITATION_4] , suggesting that less invasive spinal surface stimulation could also be effective in cortically triggered conditioning.",
